free_txt: The 2 MeV Van de Graaff injector and
the 12 MeV Van de Graaff tandem accelerator were used.
Two surface barrier detectors of 500 omega*cm
resistivity coupled to Ortec model 103-203 amplifiers.
One detector was fixed at a suitable angle as a
monitor.

Reference related
to the first method of monitoring.
Three methods were used to
determine absolute cross sections. 1.The present data
were related to be absolute cross section measurements
by comparison of yield at alpha particle energies of
4.0 and 6.6 MeV at angle of 71.55, 106.60 and 136.06
degr. which were common to both sets of data. 2.Gas
target measurements using natural CO2 were carried out
at alpha particle energies of 6.6, 7.4 and 8.4 MeV and
angles of 60, 71.55 and 90 degr. employing a gas cell
with thin nickel beam entrance and exit windows and a
mylar window for the reaction products. The gas
pressure (22 mm of mercury) and temperature were
monitored continuously. Beam integration was achieved
using a calibrated integrator, tested before and after
the measurements and accurate to better than 1%. 3. The
proton energy equivalents of several of the carbon
foils used in the 12C(a,a0) measurements were
determined for incident energies between 300 keV and
1.8 MeV, using the method of target modulation.)
The targets consisted of thin, self-supporting foils
of natural carbon of 20 mu-g/cm2 thickness. A very thin
gold layer was evaporated onto the foils to enable
checking of beam integration and detector angle
settings by means of Rutherford scattering.
